## 1. GitHub vs GitLab

| Feature | GitHub | GitLab |
|---|---|---|
| **Owner** | Microsoft | GitLab Inc. |
| **Primary Focus** | Open-source collaboration & social coding | Full DevOps lifecycle platform |
| **CI/CD** | GitHub Actions (external integrations) | Built-in CI/CD pipelines |
| **Self-Hosting** | GitHub Enterprise (paid) | GitLab CE (free) & EE (paid) |
| **Issue Tracking** | Basic (Issues, Projects) | Advanced (Boards, Milestones, Epics) |
| **Container Registry** | GitHub Packages | Built-in Container Registry |
| **Auto DevOps** | ❌ Not available | ✅ Available |
| **Wiki** | ✅ Available | ✅ Available |
| **Pages** | GitHub Pages | GitLab Pages |
| **Security Scanning** | Basic (via Actions) | Built-in SAST, DAST, Dependency Scan |
| **Pricing** | Free tier + Pro/Team/Enterprise | Free CE + Starter/Premium/Ultimate |

### Key Differences Summary

- **GitHub** is more popular for open-source projects and developer community. It has a larger ecosystem and marketplace.
- **GitLab** is an all-in-one DevSecOps platform. It integrates code hosting, CI/CD, monitoring, and security scanning in one place.
- **Self-hosting**: GitLab CE can be self-hosted for free, making it popular for enterprises wanting full data control.
- **CI/CD**: GitLab's built-in CI/CD is more tightly integrated and powerful out of the box compared to GitHub Actions.

