## 2. GitLab CE vs GitLab EE

### GitLab Community Edition (CE)
- **Free and Open Source** (MIT License)
- Self-hosted on your own server
- Core Git features: repositories, merge requests, issues, wikis
- Basic CI/CD pipelines
- Container Registry
- GitLab Pages
- Suitable for: small teams, startups, individual developers, and companies wanting full control

### GitLab Enterprise Edition (EE)
- **Paid (Proprietary License)**
- Available as SaaS (gitlab.com) or self-hosted
- Includes everything in CE, plus:

| EE Feature | Description |
|---|---|
| **Epics & Roadmaps** | Plan work across multiple projects |
| **Group-level security** | Security dashboards for entire groups |
| **DAST / SAST** | Dynamic & Static Application Security Testing |
| **Dependency Scanning** | Detect vulnerable dependencies |
| **License Compliance** | Check open-source license risks |
| **Advanced CI/CD** | Multi-project pipelines, merge trains |
| **Geo Replication** | Mirror repos across geographic regions |
| **LDAP / SAML / SSO** | Enterprise authentication |
| **Service Desk** | Turn emails into issues |
| **Priority Support** | Direct support from GitLab team |

### EE Tiers
| Tier | Best For |
|---|---|
| **Free** | Individuals (gitlab.com) |
| **Premium** | Growing teams needing advanced CI/CD |
| **Ultimate** | Enterprises needing full DevSecOps |

